intended_learning_outcomes_of_course.value:
By the end of the course students will be able to:
Write simple programs involving elementary Haskell techniques, including pure function definitions; 
Define new algebraic data types and use recursion to define functions that traverse recursive types, and use common higher-order functions such as map, fold, and filter;
Demonstrate understanding of how to express data structures and function interfaces using types, and how to infer types;
Understand parametric polymorphism, and ad-hoc polymorphism through typeclasses;
Demonstrate understanding of the differences between strict and lazy evaluation, and the tradeoffs of the two approaches;
Demonstrate understanding of how to structure programs using monads, how to use the most common standard monads (including IO, Maybe, and State), and how to use a monad transformer;
Understand and use common functional abstractions such as functors and applicative functors;
Develop substantial functional software applications including external libraries;
Use formal methods and property-based testing to reason about the correctness of functional programs;
Construct, adapt, and analyse code using standard Haskell tools such as Stack and HUnit
